      <hedline>
        <hl1>Nassau Sheriff Says Reforms Are Under Way</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Nassau County Sheriff Edward Reilly, in move intended to save county $300,000 a year, ends policy of letting workers take their Correction Department vehicles home at night; comptroller Frederick E Parola recommended shift (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The Nassau County sheriff, Edward Reilly, who assumed the post in February, says he has changed how his department operates its fleet of 127 vehicles, following recommendations by the county comptroller that could save the financially troubled county $300,000 a year.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>The Nassau County sheriff, Edward Reilly, who assumed the post in February, says he has changed how his department operates its fleet of 127 vehicles, following recommendations by the county comptroller that could save the financially troubled county $300,000 a year.</p>
        <p>A review by the comptroller, Frederick E. Parola, found that 71 of the 127 Correction Department vehicles were assigned to people who were allowed to take them home each night. Mr. Parola said the department could save money by ending that practice.</p>
        <p>METRO NEWS BRIEFS: NEW YORK</p>
      </block>
